rComments: Best Prof I've had so far. She is caring and really loves what she does. She makes chemistry a lot easier to understand and will answer all questions. At the start of classes, she shared stories and at the end of the semester, we had a virtual pet parade.

My favorite prof so far at uni. Had orgo in person and so happy I did because this prof was super good at explaining. Great energy and nice to students, answers questions after class. Tests were challenging (averages for both midterms around 50 or 60) but nothing unexpected, she gives old tests which are nearly identical. Hard class but survivable.

Highly recommend Dr. Fox! She is organized, explains clearly and always available outside of class. She does provide many ressources which I would use according to your needs - they all don't need to be used. Overall a great experience and I hope to have Dr. Fox again in the future.
I took a course with this prof, I should have checked how much the positive reviews are downvoted and not just the rating.

Very kind prof who cares about her students success. Always willing to clarify or answer questions. Used Chem101 software for testing - which was not the best software in my opinion. (I took this class virtually). But overall great prof, very approachable.
Avoid this prof at any cost.

I was terrified of university-level chemistry and I'm so glad I had Dr. Fox as my prof! She's great at explaining concepts that I had a lot of trouble with in high school, and is incredibly patient and helpful with answering questions after class. However, you really need to be ready to work hard in her class!

Dr. Fox is so kind, caring, and she's such a great person. Her lectures, course organization, and teaching style definitely suits a lot of people's style of learning. It just really didn't suit me though. I felt bombarded by resources. A lot of the time the DGDs would cover different topics. There was SO much to keep up with.
long and difficult tests, but she gives lots of practice and a few small extra credit options

Dr. Fox is really caring, she provided a free textbook, and she posted a lot of practice problems. However, videos are posted prior to the lectures, and then class time is used as a dgd, so you have to watch 2 lectures for each class. The exams were long and harder than the practice problems. She's very nice but makes you work to get a good mark.

I LOVE HER. her lecture videos are the type of videos you would want to watch on youtube, she is very clear and informative. I love chem and she didn't ruin it for me. I recommend her yall. and her tests are fair and easy. if you do the quizzes you get a 5% bonus throughout the term. she is nice, caring, and sweet. labs are very useful as well.

She seems as if she really cares about her students. It's just that she's very lecture heavy and often continues teaching after class ends. Her tests are way harder than the homework and she gives SO much homework. Her explanation videos were super helpful but extremely long. It felt like I was neglecting my other coursework to not fail this one.

Because Dr. Fox is a really nice person I wish I could say this class was enjoyable. She was really understanding and you can tell she is trying to be a good teacher but there is just so much extra work that this class felt like 3 instead of one. Her tests were also a lot harder than the practice questions so make sure you understand them well.

She is an AMAZING teacher! She provided so many resources (extra dgds/office hours, more practice, pre-lecture theory videos, textbook, and participation quizzes) that were not mandatory but were for our benefit. She cares so much about her students, listens to their concerns, and takes extra time to answer questions. I highly recommend her!
Very interesting prof!! Made online lectures interesting and really cares about her students!

Dr Fox is extremely nice but seems to forget we are balancing 5 courses. There are pre-lecture videos (30 mins), lectures ALWAYS go overtime (2hr+), and 3 discussion groups per week. If you are able to manage your time, she is worth the in depth explanations but I felt this was an unnecessary workload and found myself devoting all my time to chem

Dr. Fox is a really nice professor. She explains everything super well and she's always willing to ask questions. The only thing I didn't like about her course is that you have to watch the lectures on your own time and class time is used for review and problem solving (like DGD's). This really affected my motivation and caused me to fall behind.

Dr. Fox is super sweet, especially through emails, however she provides TOO many resources, and one hour pre lecture videos before each lectures. She overcomplicates topics (IMO) making concepts even more confusing and isnt clear and concise, sorry. TOO many DGDS, CHEM101, 2 Textbooks, lots of lectures! If you want her to teach you, expect lots!
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Lecture heavy', 'Lots of homework']

rComments: Took orgo1 in french with her and it was amazing. Lectures went overtime, but with online class it doesn't matter too much. Always reexplains things if you have questions, draws everything out during the lecture, and slides are very organized. Honestly, if she is teaching orgo1 again, take it with her you won't regret it!

Dr. Fox is the best prof I had in all of first year online. She is nice and actually cares and listens to her students. You can tell that she works really hard to create a good online space. The course content was not easy and you need to work hard and practice to do well but the course set-up (especially online) was a good as it gets.
Content is hard but she tries very hard to explain things well and gives many opportunities to get help. Reweighs tests very well to give u the best mark possible. Very nice and easy to listen to.
Dr. Fox Is great because she's really good at simplifying things and doesn't assume that everybody already knows everything, so she takes her time in explaining concepts.

Dr Fox is amazing and the negative comments arent true at all you will see yourself. Most people gave her bad ratings because its first year and they got disappointed that they didnt get the 90 that they used to get in high school thats completely normal. Im a second year student and I can tell she cares! Plus she calculated marks fairly!!!!!
This rating has been removed as per our site guidelines.

After reading the last few reviews, I am shocked. Fox was an amazing prof. I never did well in highschool chem, but Fox's lectures were really well explained and the assignments helped reinforce the material. Fox always answered emails and even looked over tests to remark. She did everything she could to give us the highest mark possible.

I am shocked with the last few ratings. She did NOT change any of the marks and she did NOT recalculate the marks diffèrent ways to ensure students got the highest marks. In fact, she promised to add a few marks to the lowest test which she did NOT do. Other profs dropped the lowest test mark. Tests were brutal. Take in French: they had no labs.

I probably destroyed my eternal soul doing this class, but I would do it again. There's a lot (30 min pre-lec, CHEM 101, textbook), and if this is your only chem class, you may want to take another prof. Otherwise, it'll break you down and build you up. If you don't have time for the textbook, do the other TAs DGD questions.

Ok she's really not as bad as everyone before is making her seem. Yes, her lectures 2+ hours, yes the problems in class don't match the mid terms (just go to DGDs & pay attention to assignments), but she really takes her time (she calculated everyone's mark SEVEN ways so we get the best). If that's not caring, idk what is. Don't be underestimate!

although her lectures were a bit long (2 + hrs sometimes), she still managed to make class fun and made sure to explain stuff in detail so that everyone understands the material. chemistry is not an easy subject, and of course you are expected to do some extra practice, just make sure you ask for help and attend DGDs and you'll be fine!!

amazing prof. make sure you show up to class AND DO EVERY ASSIGNMENT QUESTION. those tend to show up a lot on exams and tests. DGD questions are also important. She shifted the weightings to give everyone the highest grade possible. shows how caring she is!!

VERY caring and understanding prof. Her exam questions were straight from assignments and DGDs. People just missed that. Make sure you show up to class and understand the content. I have truly never understood chemistry before until I took 1311 with her. You will not regret it!!!

Dr. Fox is very passionate about chemistry, and it shows in her teaching. She is very clear and easy to listen to. There is a textbook, but it is optional. Keep in mind I took this during covid... Only downside -- she has a lot of students, so it sometimes takes a while to get a response from her by email. Great prof!!

95% of the material in the course must be self-taught. She expects students to teach themselves. Exams contain materials that were never talked about in the lectures or even in the textbook. Honestly, you should socially distance yourself from any of her classes!!!

Her expectations for a first year course are too high, expecting them to think like a PhD candidate. Expect 3x the workload as other classes, including her famous 2+ hr lectures which are useless because her exam questions won't reflect what you learned in her eternal lectures. Don't take this class with her, take it with someone else, seriously.
teacherRatingTags: ['Test heavy', 'Get ready to read', 'Lots of homework']

rComments: I am a hard working student and dedicated MANY hours to this class over the semester. Unfortunately, the midterms and exam were much harder than expected. Most of the content is a review/build on grade 12 chem, however, her exam questions don't reflect what she taught. No matter how much you study, be prepared to not end with the grade you hope for

Worst chem class ever! She spends more time talking and explaining material that is not relevant to what she will test us on. She is aware that she does that and is frank about that - yet she doesn't match her exam questions to what she teaches. Insanely heavy course load. Take this class with other profs if you care about your GPA!

She's goes into TOO much unecessary details. I had to either Youtube everything or use my highschool knowledge to understand anything. She was of no help! Not recommended! I would advise you to take this class with either Mayer or Sandro. Their class workload is more realistic unlike Fox who expects you to invest 30 hours/week into her class alone.

Horrible prof. This goes to show you that uOttawa hires anyone to teach their students. She is very boring and her content does not reflect content on her unfair and long exams. She should not be allowed to teach. I am convinced that the decent reviews are written by her. Students should file a complaint together.
Only the worst professor in the science faculty. Her tests do not make sense and she lacks empathy towards students. Stay away from her.
The only prof who requires you to attend ALL three DGD sections. If you don't want to devote 90% of your week to one class, don't take this class with her!

Dr. Fox is an amazing teacher. All her notes are clear and even tho lectures are long, you can skip them and watch the recording at 2x the speed. Everything on the midterms and exam were reasonable with one hard question. She says in the beginning of her course attend the DGDs, which most didnt. PS- THE HARDEST QUESTION COMES FROM THE DGD!

Dr. Fox is an amazing prof that is able to clearly communicate what is expected of you. Even though I feel I could have done better in this class, her teaching style is very efficient and helpful. As long as you do the work, you will receive a good mark. Her lectures are also very useful as she does the worksheets with the class.

Dr. Fox was a great prof for general chem. Her lectures were very thorough (often too long as there were pre-recorded videos to watch prior to lectures AND zoom lectures with practice problems). As long as you review the problems from class and the homework on CHEM101, you should be more than prepared for the midterms and exam (which are fair).

Her lectures are repetitive and it takes her a long time to finish saying the same sentence, like, four or five different times. She was quite snappy with me over email when I asked her to consider redistributing my worst midterm to my best one. The exams would be easier if only it didn't contain questions that were not covered in class.

She is not concise at all when lecturing and is rather poor at explaining concepts. Her marking scheme is extremely rigid despite the ambiguity/open-ended nature of her questions. The exam was far too long, and not fair at all. It had many random questions that were not covered in her 2 hr lectures. I would avoid this prof if I were you.

I believe that people were too hard on Dr. Fox this semester. They forget how hard it is to go from many years of in-person teaching to online in just 2 semesters. I believe that Dr. Fox did extraordinary in her teaching, given the circumstances. I would absolutely take her again, and I hope to take another one of her courses in the future.

Dr. Fox is a super caring and fair professor. Her lectures are super clear since she goes slowly and step by step. The questions covered in the lectures/worksheets are VERY SIMILAR to those on the midterms/final. If you practice those & do chem 101 + textbook hw, you can def get an A. You won't regret taking Dr. Fox's class!

THE WORST PROF I HAVE EVER HAD. She gives 1 or 2 east examples on each concept but then expects you to be able to solve hard questions in her exams. She has this annoyingly slow tone that will drive you insane during her 2 hour lectures. She expects you to know every concept like you're a chemist IN A FIRST YEAR CLASS. Avoid her!!

She is a great teacher that wants people to do well. However, you HAVE to do all of the hw, many of the questions on the exam are either from Chem101 or the textbook (people say some of the questions weren't covered but they were in the hw). She teaches really well, but her office hours are the best if you don't understand material.

Worst first year course I took. Had a lot of expectations as she had high ratings prior to fall 2020 but she made my life miserable. She tends to forget that most of us are just first years. Her classes are very dry and boring, and they DO NOT reflect the exam questions. Do yourself a favour and don't even bother taking any course with her.

The fact that she thinks she can teach is laughable. Too bad none of her jokes were. Actually she just tells one joke: "Chemists are lazy. No we are practical!" Anyways don't take this class with her unless you want unfair and very difficult midterms and exam with random questions you have NEVER seen in her boring, time-defying lectures.

She's goes into TOO much unecessary details. I had to either Youtube everything or use my highschool knowledge to understand anything. She was of no help. Not recommended! If I had to do it again, I would take it with another prof.

I'll save myself the trouble of repeating what others have said: if you really wanna know whether or not to take her class, look at the reviews from fall 2020 to get an idea of what it's gonna be like. Very heavy workload: pre recorded videos, >2hr lectures, DGDs (she expects you to attend ALL 3 SECTIONS), textbook questions and chem 101 questions

Dr. Fox made me hate being at uOttawa. Her exam was disgustingly long and intensely tough. She showed very little remorse to our concerns and did not want to drop our worst midterm when other chem profs did so. She made my life a living hell during these 4 months. Thank you Dr. Fox for making me even more depressed and anxious :)

Dr. Fox is the harshest professor I've ever seen. Shes the type of professor that doesn't like her students to get an A+ even if they work hard. I mean there's no reason why she made the exam very difficult; she's not great at teaching and exam content DOESN'T REFLECT what she gave. LIFESAVING ADVICE: DON'T TAKE THE CLASS WITH HER

Her lectures are very dry and always over the 1.5hr time limit. Her tests are known to be very difficult and long. You need to study extensively for her midterms and exam to do well because none of the stuff you learned in her lectures will be on the exams. When teaching she is very vague and doesn't do very well explaining concepts in more detail.

It is really ironic that Fox specializes in chem education when she does not know how to teach gen chem. She expects 1st year students to be PhD students and tests them based on advanced questions that were not taught in class. Maybe it would be better if she goes back to photochem and leave chem education to people who can ACTUALLY teach

Dr. Fox didn't teach anything in her 2hr lectures since material given DID NOT reflect what was on the exams which were long, difficult and unfair. She has no empathy and does not take students' concerns seriously. My anxiety and depression from the pandemic worsened, thanks to her. I am helping you by writing this review, avoid her at all cost!!!

Typical Fox's lecture consists of: her boring scuba diving videos, useless announcements, "conversely", "in other words", repeating the same point over and over again, "in other words", "consequently", continually going on irrelevant tangents, "you'll learn this in (insert upper year chem class)" and "in other words". In other words, avoid her!

She puts on a facade in which she acts like she cares about her students but in reality, she only cares about hitting a certain class average. She is adamant about dropping the worst midterm OR redistributing your worst midterm to your best one. Her midterms were hard and her exam was BRUTAL. Avoid her!!

Absolutely terrible prof, the worst one I've had in three years. She may as well be talking to himself during lectures. Can't complete a full sentence without going off on tangents. Her lectures are complete trash and she makes no effort to make them concise as she always goes over the time limit.
Worst prof. Avoid at all cost. Her test questions are awful and most of them are stuff she didn't even teach in class. She thinks we're all chemists. Stay away from her class!!!

Nice person, but terrible lecturer. She always goes overtime. Her 1.5 hr lectures become at least 2 hour lectures. Very hard exams as the exam questions are nothing like the lecture questions. Avoid taking it with her as possible. I ended up having to learn much of it on my own despite attending every class.

Dr. Fox is excellent. She ensured all students concerns were addressed throughout this odd semester, and tried her best to accommodate everyone. The content may be heavy, but thats expected with a university-level science course. Class test averages this year were even higher than previous years, yet Dr. Fox still sought ways to help boost marks.

Dr. Fox was a very entertaining and kind prof but her lectures always went over time and she had long pre-lecture videos that were needed to comprehend the lecture. The problems she does in class are pretty general compared to how applied they are on exams but she provides lots of resources to help. It was a hard class but hey thats university.

Dr. Fox is so knowledgable, goes very slow-paced which gives you sufficient time to absorb even complex topics, and provides all the resources you need to do well. If you just DO & UNDERSTAND the textbook questions, CHEM101, and the in-class worksheets then it is BEYOND possible to perform well. The exam was MORE than fair :) Def recommend.

She's a horrible teacher. She only goes through basic questions in her lectures because she expects you to apply the concepts on her advanced exam questions which why her exams are way too difficult and complicated. If you're taking gen chem with her, switch to a different section. If you can't, then I wish you good luck lol

Worst prof I have ever had. She has such surreal expectations and expects you to understand concepts as if you're a physics major. She always goes overtime with her lectures and her lectures are useless and do not reflect the content in her exam questions. Grading scheme is rough. Don't take gen chem with her.
Her tests are very difficult for a 1st year class. I practiced weeks for the final and still think i did horrible. Avoid her class

Great person, terrible prof. She loves chemistry which is clear, but she went almost double overtime for every lecture. Even when you study hard, the midterms are unfair and have the hardest questions of a topic with no in-class examples resembling them. I would recommend you to take this class with any prof except her.

Dr. Fox is an amazing professor. She is so sweet and considerate. Amazing at explaining concepts in many ways if needed. Midterms & exams are tough but fair. Do the assignments - they are very helpful for the tests. Reachable outside of class.

Throughout my 4 years in chem, I've never had Dr. Fox as a prof which is why I was very excited last summer to learn that she will be teaching my polymer class this fall. I was expecting this class to be good but it was an extremely horrible experience. She's overrated. I think she's really nice but she cannot teach at all.

Very very lecture heavy. She makes gen chem ridiculously hard, for someone who just starts uni it will be insanely hard to do well. She made us sit through 2 hr lectures while we still had chem 101 homework, textbook questions and DGD. She does not give anything substantial in her reviews for the midterm/final so beware

She expected too much from 1st year students. Hard grader, who did not give enough info on her testing criteria. Lectured were long (2+hr), and many times irrelevant, and exam questions did not reflect the content we saw in her lectures. I would avoid taking any chm 1311 with her If I were you

Expect to hear the same joke "Chemists are lazy. No they are practical!". What's a joke is that she thinks she's funny. Also expect to hear these phrases during her boring 2 hour lectures: "in other words", "conversely" and "consequently". Midterms and exam do not reflect the questions she taught. In other words, avoid taking any class with her.

She looks pretty and seems like a nice person. That is pretty much I can say about her as a prof because she expects you to teach yourself the concepts and apply them to her random exam questions. I would socially distance away from her class if I were you.

Her lectures are actually longer than they are supposed to because she rambles a lot and talks extremely slow. The worst part is that there was no point in listening to her talk for 3 hours each lecture because the midterm and exam questions are completely different from the one she taught in class. For the love of God & your GPA don't take her!!!

She was okay in terms of teaching but her midterms and exam were very difficult for a 1st year science class. I like her personality but I wouldn't take her again in any class if given the chance. I would avoid her if I were you

Yeah she seems like a nice person. However her niceness do not translate to teaching. Her midterms and exam questions were above and beyond from the basic ones she taught us in class. I wish she taught those advanced questions in her class instead of basic ones. Good luck to all who gets stuck with Fox

She seemed to be a nice enough person but lectures were slow and boring. Also the content discussed in the lectures were not reflected on the midterms and exam which they were unpredictable. It was very hard to study for them even if you finished all of the homework and textbook questions. It felt like she made them purposely hard to lower class %.

Fox is a decent lecturer, however as a prof she puts too much emphasis on problem-based learning leaving those of us who are not natural chemists scratching our heads. Midterms and exam looked nothing that was given to us on assignments and were made intentionally difficult to lower the final class %.

While she is nice, expext nothing from her. She makes you sit through 2 hour zoom lecture for each lecture. Gives you very simple and similar questions in class, and expects you to know more and beyond in the midterms and exams. Midterms and exam are absolute hell.

Self-explanatory, study hard, get good grades. One huge thing is that people expect the curriculum from her notes to be word for word on the exam, although it won't be exactly the same (like how math questions won't be the exact same from your practice as an example). She's very caring of the students, besides that, just be wary of studying hard!
She's a nice person but her midterms and final were difficult. I found that the examples she went through in class didn't prepare me for the midterms or final.

An AMAZING prof, my favourite for sure. She explains concepts clearly, is passionate about chem and cares for her students. Go to DGDs (Alisha's) and do chem101 assignments, those WILL appear on the test. I wish the lecture problems reflected what was covered on the tests better. Watch recorded lectures at 2x speed if u lack time. Overall the BEST!

Amazing person and extremely clear presenter. Passionate. Super smart. However, her exam guidelines need to be improved. Exams did not reflect information covered in class, nor the textbook per se, and they were extremely difficult.

To be honest, she is a very thorough lecturer but her exams are brutal because you won't most of the questions she went through in her lectures on your exams. Good (but very slow) lectures and bad exams. She is passionate and somewhat cares about her students (just don't talk about curving grades; she hates it).

Just simply horrible, she always goes over the time limit of 1.5 hours and makes her lectures over 2 hours. She does easy examples during the lecture but gives extremely hard questions on midterms/finals. She makes specific questions on midterms/finals worth 20% so if you dont get that right its over.

She's one of the most difficult, if not the most difficult prof for 1311. Her midterms and exam are nothing like the questions she goes through in her lectures. Speaking of which, each of her lecture consists of 30 min pre recorded videos and 2 hour zoom lecture. You'll have to do A LOT of practice problems and watch YouTube if you want to pass.

Expect to be devoting 75% of your week on this class alone. She thinks her class is the only class you're taking. Midterm questions are random and do not reflect what she taught in her lectures or on the DGDs. Exam was painstakingly difficult. Take her at your own risk!

Dr. Fox was my favorite prof, but keep in mind, if you want to do well, you can't just do that bare minimum: do to DGDs and go textbook problems. Midterms and exams were extremely fair, and there wasn't a single question that I had not seen before in either a DGD, in class example, or the textbook. Highly highly recommend her!!

She is one of the best profs I've had since coming to university. She is very understanding and insightful. Her lectures online were a little long but she really took the time to explain concepts. Midterms/ tests were a little hard, but they reflected DGD questions and in-class questions.

If you want a good prof who will teach concepts well then take her. If you want easy midterms then dont. This is university, the midterms should not be easy and she is incredibly clear and very knowledgeable. She will make sure you are prepared for future chem courses. Test questions were found in DGDs most of the time!
I regret taking this class with her...

Her CHM 1311 basically expects you to learn on your own since her teaching style is so abysmal that you're better off, teaching yourself rather than expect her to teach you. Btw some of these people saying that she is the best prof are lying and simping for her

What an overrated prof. I was very excited to have her, only to be disappointed by her ridiculous midterms and refusal to teach the advanced questions she puts on her midterms. Definitely avoid taking any chem classes with her. I can only imagine how horrible her orgo I class and upper year chem classes are

Her class itself is a sinkhole in the space time continuum. Each class consists of 20-30 mins recorded videos and 2-3 hrs zoom lectures. Multiply that by 2 and you're looking at spending 4-6 hrs per week on her lectures alone. Oh by the way, the basic questions in her lectures DO NOT reflect the advanced questions she puts on her midterms.

People only like her because she's cute and nice but those two things do not make a good prof. Expect to teach yourself the materials because she expects you to "apply yourself". Talk about a bad teaching style
I ended up having chem because of her. Avoid taking her class!!

Beware of the people rating her 5/5. They are your typical suck ups. It is very sad that people are kissing up to a 1st year prof who does not even know their existence. Anyways Fox is probably the hardest prof for 1311. Midterm questions do NOT resemble anything she taught in her slow and boring lectures. Avoid her at all cost!

Beware of those who grade her well. Yes, she is a kind woman and a very good lecturer. However, what she teaches in class is very basic. Questions on midterms are completely different than what is seen in class. The French course was a joke compared to the English course. French students had no 30 hour lab reports to write and midterms were a joke.
Take this class with her at your own risk!!

Dr. Fox is the definition of an amazing prof. She is caring and extremely understanding. She explains topics in-depth and DGD's are helpful to understand confusing topics. Questions from DGD's have usually appeared on the tests as well. She is funny and tries her best to understand student's concerns and helps them in order for them to succeed.
Dr. Fox is a great prof. She has been understanding, accomodating throughout the semester. She explains topics well but you do have to do practice questions to solidify your understanding.

Dr. Fox is a fantastic prof. She posted video examples before class that was mostly theory-based so that you could broaden your understanding of the topic. She went through many examples in class and tests were mostly made up of similar DGD examples as well as examples from assignments. She is a caring prof who is setting up her students to succeed

Dr. Fox's lectures are extremely draining and always go much longer than the class time. Each one of her lessons consists of a video, a quiz, and an assignment, all on top of the actual lecture, extremely time consuming. The tests are not at all similar to the questions you do in class and for practice. Very hard class.

She talks very slow which is why her lectures take forever to finish. It wouldn't be as bad if only the problems she goes through in her lectures are on the midterms/exam. Expect to see random questions on the midterms/exam because she wants you to think like a PhD student. I think she forgot this is a 1st year class. Anyways, avoid her

One of the tougher profs for Gen chem. Avoid her unless you're really good at either chem or physics. If you want an easy A, then you will definitely want to avoid her for Gen chem. She doesn't curve the grades because she is very uptight and has this "holier than thou" attitude when it comes to grades. One of the worst profs I have ever had.

She is the best. Sometimes she stays an hour after class to help; she does hw questions, extra problems, so stop complaining about long lectures. The test questions are very similar to textbook questions - you have to do that hw (but if you do all the hw, you will get 95%) .She cares so much about students, and is always accessible for help.

Her midterms don't reflect the questions from lecture? That's not even accurate. She can't make her own questions because she's restricted by a question bank, but Qs on the midterm are based on the exact same concepts she teaches you in class. Her midterms are fair and she's been generous with marking. Fox is great, these ratings are just sad.
I adore Dr. Fox. She is so warm, kind and genuinely so engaging. You can tell she really understands what she's taking about. I would take her again in a heartbeat.

She is actually overrated. She takes forever to make her point and she ALWAYS goes overtime which is why her lectures are 4-6 hours per week. Not to mention, you can never prepare for her midterms because her midterm questions are completely different than the ones she showed in lectures.
Her midterm questions are nothing like the questions she went through in her lectures. Avoid her!!

Professor Fox is the most caring professor I have encountered. She genuinely wants you to do well in her class and she is available to assist you when you need help. Although, the midterms did not reflect the content taught in class and the labs take up to 30 hours to write. This class is just a lot of work but that is not entirely Dr. Fox's fault.

Are you aware that the French students had no lab reports to write? They did lab simulations and quizzes that they were allowed to redo until they got 100%.. We spent 30 hours on each report and questions were constantly changed because of their ambiguity. Dr. Fox assessments and assignments are brutal and dont reflect course content. Avoid her.
Worst class ever. Avoid her for every chem class if possible!!

Dr Fox is an AMAZING professor who truly cares about the success of her students, especially with covid. She assigns plenty of textbook problems to help prepare for midterms . The midterms were all fair, just be ready to study. She's great at explaining topics in a simple way, and you can tell she's passionate about her job. Loved her class!
Loved Dr. Fox, I never found her lectures boring. But I found that the exams did not reflect what we learned in class and were pretty difficult compared to the worksheets she walked us through.

Dr. Fox is a very good lecturer and explains concepts quite well. However, her example problems are lacking difficulty and do not reflect the questions on the midterm exams. She does not assign textbook work yet I found the textbook to be the only reason I passed tests. Her questions are way above standard and much more difficult than other classes

Dr. F is a great lecturer; however she only covers very basic questions during her lessons. Midterm and assignment questions are beyond the first year chemistry curriculum which is extremely concerning. The French class is much easier and they also have no lab reports to write. We feel that the University should look into this.

Dr. Fox is an excellent teacher. She explains concepts clearly. However, the exam questions during Covid, did not reflect many of the types of questions we covered in the lectures, nor were they similar to the textbook questions. The questions she does in class are very basic compared to what we are being tested on during exams.
Great professor. Provides lots of oppertunities to help encourage better learning in the classroom, and creates ways for students to get extra marks to increase their grade. Group exams are the best.

Best prof I've had so far. Fox will explain things down to the very basic foundations so you can understand questions step for step. She is very accessible, and will answer any and all questions. Highly recommend attending her DGDs or watching their recordings, because those questions will appear on her tests!

She's the best prof I've known so far and very generous for students to earn an extra mark on the exam and midterms as she adds a bonus question. Make sure you do the assignment cuz it counts and boosts your final mark if your midterm's grade is unexpected.

Great prof to have your first year. Had her for gen chem and for Orgo I. She is amazing at explaining concepts simply and dose many practice questions in class. She shares her previous midterms and exams with the class, they are VERY similar to her test. Also really easy to meet outside of her office hours.
Super prof, almost the best I have ever seen. Feeling lucky to be taught by her.
Solid prof, an A is definitely doable if you put in the work. She provides old exams and reuses questions from those exams on her midterms and final.
Best class at uOttawa, the prof is always there to help and answer questions, totally recommend if you enjoy chem
great prof. would take again.

Dr. Fox is one of the most organized teachers I've ever had. The material is not easy, but if you do all her homework assignments, DGD worksheets, etc. you will be very well prepared for the exams. She is so caring and understanding towards her students. I love this woman with my whole heart

Dr Fox is amazing! She's really good at explaining concepts. Midterms are done in 2 stages, boosting your mark :) DO SAPLING!! (you can get bonus marks) As long as you go to class/dgds and practice q's often you will get an A in her class

Absolutely fantastic. Great personality, starts most lecture with videos of her scuba diving. Sapling can be a little hard, but easy to google, and easy points. the textbook is very helpful for homework, but it is not needed. Lots of extra credit. Her expectations are clear. She gives you all her old exams and midterms. She rocks!!!

She is a really good prof. Her power points are very well organised. She has tones of practice exams on brightspace. She cares a lot about teaching and about her students' success. There is alot of extra credit assignments.

Dr. Fox gives the hardest midterms and exams compared to all the other chemistry profs but is the best lecturer. She is a great prof if you attend lectures and pay attention. She gives all of the previous midterms and finals, use the finals to help study for the midterms because she pulls question from there.

By far my favorite prof! If you are planning on taking chem passed first year CHM1311 and CHM1321 with Dr. Fox is the way to go, there are easier profs but she'll prepare you super well for upper year chem classes. And although her classes aren't easy it's definitely possible to do well if you put in the work!

Dr. Fox is an amazing teacher. She records her lectures and DGDs which really helps. MAKE SURE you do all of her previous midterms and exams that she posts since the tests are about 80% recycled questions. It is also a good idea to do Sappling + you can get extra credit: I got almost 12/10 on the homework section.

Dr. Fox is amazing. I had her for CHM1311 and CHM1321. She is a strong lecturer and provides MANY resources right on the course website. YOU NEED TO ACTUALLY WORK HARD. You can only do good on her tests if you actually do homework because her test questions are integrative. She isn't lying when she says she's the hardest 1st year chem prof

Good at teaching the material & gives examples in class. Did not use the textbook. Her midterms & exams are difficult but not impossible. Practice ALL of the past exams before the exams & you will do well. ATTEND THE DGD'S, DO SAPLING, and answer ALL the questions on the exams for PART MARKS even if you are lost (they are very generous)!!!!!

Super nice and funny. Very clear in her teaching and answers questions well, makes you did midterms in groups which was a mark-booster for some people but personally I didn't like it. Posts all old midterms and exams online for you to study from.

Dr. Fox was a good prof who was very organized, provided a lot of resources to study and she records her lectures on echo360. She is very passionate about chemistry and her classes are engaging. However, she is one of the more tougher profs for first year general chemistry. Her midterms and finals weren't easy. Be prepared!

Dr. Fox is an amazing prof and cares a lot about her students and their success. She alway made herself available to help and posts years old old practice midterms and exams which you should DEFINITELY study! She's so energetic even at 8:30 in the morning but very passionate about chemistry and her students.

Coming from someone who hates chem, Dr. Fox made this class fun and engaging. She was really funny and full of energy! Her exams were totally fair, and almost all her questions are recycled from previous years (and she posts all of them with answer keys!!). To do well, do the Sapling, work hard in labs, and make sure to study using the old exams!

she was a great a professor but the class isn't easy. i went in with a strong background from a grade 12 which really helped me. i bought the textbook but it was useless tho, if you want an A+ study for the midterms and finals using old exams that are on her website. use chegg to help with online homework and labs.

Dr. Fox is an amazing prof for chemistry! She posts all of her past midterms and finals (with answers) and she repeats a lot of the questions. Her lectures are a little bit all over the place, so it definitely helps if you have a strong knowledge of chemistry coming out of high school. Overall, great prof if you're willing to put in a little work.
teacherRatingTags: ['Gives good feedback', 'Clear grading criteria', 'Lots of homework']

rComments: Great prof, chemistry isn't really my strong suit, but she sort of helped me appreciate it a bit more. Make sure to do past midterms and finals, she recylces many questions and if I made sure to do all of them I would have done better. Labs and Sapling do help a lot as well, so make sure to do those well. Overall, I really liked dr Fox!

Dr. Fox is an excellent prof! Always willing to give extra help to students, and very engaging during lectures. Make sure to attend class for participation marks, and if you opt into Sapling, make sure that you put in a consistent effort. You can really boost your grade!

Homework was brutal, but extra credit is available. Lectures are extremely well-structured and organized. If every teacher taught like her, people would learn stuff. Tests were a little difficult, but not unfair. Participation worth 5%. She tries to be funny, but isn't always the best at it. Regardless, her lectures were very clear. Great prof.

Dr. Fox is incredibly happy to teach first year chem. She is a great prof who explains chemistry well. Her first midterm is usually easy, but the 2nd midterm is very hard. Dr. Fox repeats her sayings often, which leads to some annoyance, but she does record lectures (video and audio), and she weighs her exams lightly compared to others.

This was literally my best class this semester because Dr. Fox is such an amazing prof. she takes her time to explain every single thing so well and the classes are recorded so you don't have to worry about missing much (advisable to go through because you get participation marks). if you also choose to do sapling, she gives extra cred assignments!
The best chemistry teacher in uottawa by far. Singly recommend her if you want to pass chemistry. Everything is well existing in class and the homework is very little compared to other classes.

10/10 prof! She is extremely knowledgable and clearly loves teaching, she is also great for help outside of class she'll answer your questions& explain concepts for as long as it might take. Her evaluations aren't super easy, but honestly for the amount of resources you have available to you just from being in her class they're fair.

The examples she does in class are way easier than exam questions and homework! Often I would understand the lecture perfectly and then find it impossible to do the homework afterwards. Don't make the mistake of focusing your studying too much on her lectures because the content of the exam is way harder than the lecture content.

Loved Dr. Fox!! Although harder than Ogilvie she is clear, caring, accessible outside of class, organized, and she gives lots of practice questions + chances to improve your grade. The course is tougher than it seems so don't be fooled. Get the textbook, practice the mechanisms, and ask questions!! practice is the key to doing well here.
teacherRatingTags: ['Gives good feedback', 'Tough grader', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: AMAZING PROF! She is very passionate, caring, respected, easy to follow, clear and organized. Gives lots of chances to get extra marks (assignments, quiz, extra credit) and uses alot of past questions from midterms and exams! Really easy to do well in gen. chem if you do the problems!
She is a great prof! Her teaching style takes some getting used to, but it is clear. This course would have been a lot better if I didn't suck at chemistry :)

I LOVE HER!!! THANKS DR. FOX :) Although, I will admit this course is VERY content heavy and you need to be ready to learn around 50 mechanisms. She will give you previous midterms which accurately reflect the difficulty and style of questions of her current ones. Dr. Fox is super accessible outside of class. She is just such a splendid professor.

Definitely one of the better profs at uOttawa. She makes her lectures very engaging and enjoyable with her jokes and chill attitude. Yes, her exams are quite hard but if you work through the old exams that she posts then you should be A-okay. You're gonna have to work hard to get a good grade :)

She's very nice and cares about her students but she makes the course much harder than it needs to be! She spends more time explaining theory you don't need to know rather than doing examples of questions you do need to know. You don't need to attend class- attend DGDs and do the practice questions and do old midterms and exams to pass.

Dr. Fox is an amazing prof. She's easily one of the best lecturers at the entire university. Contrary to some other reviews I've read, I didn't find her to be a very tough grader. She's great at taking more difficult concepts and wording them in a way that makes it easy to understand. The final exam was much easier than other sections too. A+ PROF!

This class is super easy if u took high school chem, its the exact same thing. Dr. Fox is really great at explaning things and makes the material very clear. If you have trouble with chem, taker her. Her midterms are based off her old ones that she posts. Final was harder than the midterms but overall shes v fair! dont do sappling if u buy the book

Clearly explains and provides analogies, does practice problems in class. The Echo360 questions (in class) motivate you to go to class (it's worth 5%) and forces you to practice. Lecture recordings are easily accessible and extremely useful. Sapling questions can be hard, but an easy 10% (can get a 10/10 on sapling because of the bonus questions).

Great prof. , The most important thing in this course is the lab section, try to score the most you can through it and do your best in the lecture section and you will score an EASY C in the course. LAB SECTION IS THE MOST IMPORTANT

Good prof, explains concepts pretty well and the assessments were all pretty fair (1 quiz, 2 midterms, and final exam). Lots of opportunities to get a good mark because she does participation marks and has optional assignments which take weighting off of the midterms. Very nice, passionate, and wants her students to succeed.

Dr. Fox is an amazing prof. Her lectures are very well structured and she makes difficult concepts easy to understand. Prior to taking her course, I had heard her tests were very difficult but I didn't find this to be the case. Show up, take notes, and you'll do great. Easily one of the best profs I've ever had.
The midterms were rather easy, or rather the marking wasn't tough. Lectures aren't a huge deal, and all the slide are online so it's easy to catch up. I'd take extra credit, if you know what I mean.

Idk why people are complaining that her exams are hard. she reuses old midterms and exams. Just do the sapling homework and memorize past exams. If you know how to answer the questions from past exams you are golden, cause the concepts are the same. Put in the work, an A is a guarantee.

For everyone saying Dr. Fox is a tough grader, ask anyone in other sections how they succeeded in their next chemistry courses. Dr. Fox might make you work for your grade but it definitely pays off both on her midterms, finals and future classes. She is by far my favourite professor and she deserves a lot more credit for how amazing she is.
I just realize that i am not the only one who think Kathy is a tough grader. If you want a good grade, go take Darrin and Sandro's class. These two professors are amazing.

This course is hard but Dr Fox helps. Her lectures are really well organized and recorded on echo360 which allows you to rewatch them. Attendance is mandatory and verified. Do the practise exams because the actual exams are very similar. Great prof but tough grader.
Kathy is a OK teacher, but she doesn't know how to teach students.

Dr. Fox is a great professor, very clear with her explanations. She also provides lots of practice questions with answers to better your understanding of the material. But PRACTICE! She likes to make her midterms and finals tricky. Also, don't memorize the reactions, understand them.
Work hard in her class there is no getting around it. Do the homeworks and ace those labs, I know you think 15% isn't much but it is! She's a nice lady but her exams are not as sweet.

She is a good prof,go to class participation counts and its worth it go to her office hours with questions!!practice her previous midterms, practice problem sets, sapling assignment and questions from the book because she reuses questions a lot!! dont get discouraged by a bad grade, she adds 5% worth to the best grade and removes 5% from the worst

Department of chemistry never ceases to fail in uOttawa (take notes bio department). Fox is another solid chem prof. 1st midterm is easy, 2nd is harder. Lots of easy marks from participation, labs and homework. It's actually pretty easy  if you put some effort. Study her past exams because she pulls A LOT of content from them for current exams

Best prof I've ever had. I hated chemistry before her class.  She simplifies and explains concepts so well , and is the only prof I've had so far that truly cares about her students and tries to make herself available as much as possible for extra help. If you attend class and do the assignments, you'll have no issues in any course she's teaching!

Midterms are hard but fair, she provides previous years midterms but they offer little help, you can do well make sure you study the lectures and the DGD's. My only problem with the course is the final. It was outrageously long and the questions had no similarity to anything seen in the midterm or course. All around good prof though.

Great prof! Her explanations are simplified and make a lot of sense. Provides lots of opportunities to improve grade. Very helpful and easily approachable, is willing to sit down and explain. Exams are very fair, many of the questions are from previous exams, textbook questions , online homework assignments and DGD questions.

Really enjoyed her as a prof, coming from someone who definitely does not enjoy chemistry. Her two-stage marking for midterms were pretty nice, helped out my grades a little bit. You need to put in the work to do well in this class, but as a prof she definitely makes it seem manageable and is very helpful and supportive!

Super friendly and her lectures are easy to sit through. But what I found was that she was not super clear on what type of questions would be on the midterms/finals, which hurt my grade (she told us to use past exams for practice/studying, yet they were completely different questions). Luckily, her grading system highly favours the students.
Dr. Fox was very charming and had great lectures.  The midterms were not too difficult, but the final exam was very challenging.  Make sure you go to class because attendance is worth 5%.

Absolutely in love with Fox! She made everything seem super easy and really clear. Definitely would recommend her for gen chem because she does two-stage exams and it's almost guaranteed that it'll bring your mark up 5-10%.

She is very good at explaining concepts and is very knowledgeable, but her lectures do not quite explain everything you need to know for tests and assignments. I opted in for online hwk and it was hard to do because lack of content in lectures. Attend the DGDs for answers though. Tests and midterms were average, wasn't too hard and wasn't too easy.

Good prof, interesting lecturer, midterms and assignments are fair and easy to prepare for if you do the homework and look over the old midterms and exams. Fun to go to the lectures and worth it. Made chemistry bearable.

Dr. Fox is the absolute best! Funny, caring, and explains things really well. You have to work for your grade, but she will gladly help you in any way she can. If you do all her old midterms and exams, you'll ace them- she reuses a lot of old questions.

Dr. Fox is an awesome professor to have first year! Hey lectures are clear and engaging and she truly cares about students. The midterms and finals are all based off of old finals (that she posts on blackboard) so as long as you study those, its an easy A. Homework boosts marks but is quite tricky and textbook use is extremely minimal!

Dr. Fox is my favourite professor at the University of Ottawa. She is good at lecturing and always goes through problems step by step in class. Her DGD is really helpful, although not mandatory. Midterms and exams are very fair, she recycles questions from class and previous years. In-class participation is worth 5% of the grade, so go to class.

Best prof I had in my first semester of uni. If you need to take gen chem then take this prof!! She makes it very clear what you need to know and gives great examples for everything. She posts all her old midterms and exams which are great for studying (she recycles questions) and there is always partial points given on the tests which helps alot.
She is by far my favorite professor so far. She is hilarious and she tries very hard to make sure everyone gets the best possible mark in the course.

Hands down the best prof you could get for first year chem. most of the content was a review of high school so if you're confident in that you'll be fine.  Almost all midterm/final questions are taken from previous tests and she posted them all including solutions!!!  She's also super friendly and down to earth.  Go Dr Fox!!!

Couldn't have been happier with a first year chemistry prof! Her lectures are so clear and engaging, midterms and finals are extremely easy (exactly the same as old versions that she posts)! We also had the two stage testing this year which hooded marks significantly. Overall an awesome course with an awesome prof!

Professor Kathy is simply AMAZING!.. It is obvious that she knows what she teaches, she explains the topic so well and records all the classes including her DGDs and posts them on blackboard so one advantage is that you can skip class all semester but you would loose 5% for participation though.

Kathy might just be perhaps the worst professor I had all year. Not only is she arrogant, uncaring and flat out rude in her approach, the entire course was just a scam. From the get-go we are basically forced to buy her online assignment program, and the amount of time necessary to spend solving the assignments is literally worthless. But the thing

My favourite professor. Passionate, intelligent and inspirational Dr. Fox will keep you interested and excited for her lectures and material. Her lectures are detailed, easy to follow, lots of examples and prepares you well for the exam. Never needed the textbook once, her lectures were recorded and she gave lots of direction in her DGD's she runs.

She has an extremely rigid marking scheme. You are not tested on whether you understand the concepts, but on whether you can get your answer on paper exactly as she has it on her marking scheme.  Advice: Memorize notes and terminology and use the exact same terminology (all of it) for your answers on tests. Don't try to be creative with your words.
teacherRatingTags: ['Gives good feedback', 'Graded by few things', 'Tough grader']

rComments: Hands down the best prof I had in first year. Took her for org1 too. Super nice, makes the lectures as fun as possible, and gives lots of opportunities to increase your mark (assignments, attendance, etc.). Her notes are organized and easy to study off of. Be sure to use questions from assignments and notes to study - she reuses them on exams.

Tough course, but she's excellent as a prof. Very funny and kind, and has very clear lectures. Take good notes, review your notes, do her practice questions that she posts on blackboard, and do her old practice midterms/exams (exams are very similar to these, to the questions, and to dgd/textbook questions) and attend/watch her DGDs.

Provides step-by-step explanations on how to do mechanisms for Orgo I. Exams reflect what is covered in lectures and DGDs. DGDs are super helpful for review and new question types that are not covered in class but could be on exam. Posts previous midterms with answers, podcasts, and extra questions.
She is amazing,  so inspirational during lectures, clear explanation and the class is so enjoyable. BUT Hard Exams! beware..

Participation and labs really boost your marks, but if you fully do the old midterms and final exams you will do fine because a majority of the questions are reused. Really lovely gal and very good lecturer, highly recommend.
One of the best professors for the first year courses!

Dr. Fox is great at teaching! Put the effort into the course and you'll get an A. She takes all her test questions from old material/the textbook. She gives tons of bonus marks on homework and easy participation marks! Would take again! She's super willingly to help and great at conveying the material.

She is a great prof, will definitely help you if you need it. She is not out to punish students, she truly cares about us and our survival... If you're not the best at chemistry, or you want enjoyable yet educational classes, she's perfect.

Definitely the prof you want for gen chem! Good lecturer, helpful during office hours. Sapling and participation is essentially 15 free marks (if you put in the effort that is) and can be life savers. Midterms/final can be tough, but she reuses many questions from previous exams.
Exam is really difficult and the midterms can be tricky but everything else is straight forward.

My third course with her and she lived up to her usual awesomeness. Fantastic lectures, super useful in office hours, and gave the option for extra credit. Exams were fair but definitely not easy. Content was very interesting.

I HIGHLY RECOMMEND. Very into her job and seems to genuinely love what she does. Is very upbeat throughout her lectures and definitely creates a positive class atmosphere. Having difficulty with the material? Visit her office hours-She goes above and beyond to effectively explain and answer student questions. DO OLD MIDTERMS/EXAMS!!!!!!

I loved Dr. Fox! She is very clear and goes through solutions step by step in her lectures, so you have amazing notes for studying later! Lecture Tools and Sapling are also just really easy ways to boost your grade. She also posts old midterms and exams for you to use as study tools (DO THEM!!! She tends to recycle questions!)

During class she works on problems like most profs. However she writes them out very clearly and makes the solutions very easy to understand. You get free marks for just showing up to class and the midterms are practically the same as practice ones she gives you

Love this prof- her DGDs were great, lectures were clear and she is always willing to assist students. I never got bored in her class! DO THE OLD EXAMS/MIDTERMS, she recycles Qs!! Do the Sapling, it's a great way to raise your mark. Downside: exam questions are harder than the ones done in class. Midterms were fair, final was pretty tough.

Anyone who complains about her course has not maximised their use of resources. All her exam questions are taken from sapling (weekly online homework assignments) past exams (which she posts to her website WITH SOLUTIONS) AND DGDs (she posts the recordings on echo360). Do  textbook questions and don't opt out of sapling. Go to office hours for help

She cares about the students and does a lot of examples step-by-step in class. She also posts podcasts of her lectures and DGD through Echo360. There is an assignment every week on sapling (you have to pay for the program) and they aren't that difficult (and decrease the worth of your midterms). Do the suggested problems from the text book.
Great prof, she's really nice and makes the course fun. Midterms and exams are fair, no surprises.

Awful pacing. She spent so much time on photochem (not very useful) then realized she ran out of time and just did the rest of the material in 3 classes, which was actually useful content and was more difficult. Not enough time on exams so she could fit the BS 2-stage partner exam in. Took 4 weeks to mark exams. She is friendly and good lectur tho

Amazing lectures, does plenty of examples, explains concepts very clearly. DO OLD MIDTERMS AND EXAMS! GO TO HER DGDs! She takes questions directly from there for midterms and all her midterms are the same every year. Just do the work and you'll get an easy A.

Expect to need to do a lot of work. Consists mostly of memorizing mechanisms. Lectures are almost all just drawing mechanisms that you will need to know for the exams. It can be pretty tricky to apply the mechanisms shown in class to the exam questions. It was hard to apply the examples of the reactions to other molecules. Sapling is a life saver.

The class is basically a review of grade 12 chemistry, very few new concepts. Does lots of examples in class and in DGDs and tests reuse these questions or are very similar to them. Questions from past exams get recycled, so make sure to look over the ones she posts. Really nice and is always there to answer questions for you.

Great prof. Classes are FUN! I just followed along with slides on my laptop and wrote class problems down in a notebook. Do not opt out of Sapling. Go to Kathy's DGDs, even if they aren't your DGDs!!! Make yourself a clear list of all reactions learned that you can update throughout the semester to keep the info organized in your head.

Gen them with Dr. Fox was much easier.  Content is tougher for Chm1321, I'll give you that.  You have to work your butt off to get a good grade.  "Lecture tools" and "Sapling" were life savers for me, as well as the lab portion.  MUST WATCH her DGD podcasts.  ASK questions, don't hesitate!  Dr. Fox is a good prof for any course - just work for it!!

MUST TAKE Dr. Fox for CHM1311!  If you work hard, you get the grade!  "Lecture tools" and "Sapling" give you so many free marks.  Assignments are easy.  Go to her DGD!  She gives excellent notes and examples.  Arguably, some of her tests are tough, but she prepares you tenfold for the final.  She's AMAZING.  HIGHLY RECOMMENDED!!!
Dr. Fox was a very good lecturer and the only real downside was how fast she talks. Her past exams are super helpful - take this class if you have the chance.

AMAZING PROFESSOR! Took Org I with her and she made me love it. The content is tough but she breaks it down well. Her midterms and final are really fair. Half the questions on this year's final were pretty much taken from last year's. If you listen in lectures and take notes, do her practice problem sets and watch her DGDs, you'll do well.
I think she is a lovely person and a reasonable lecturer but her exams are ridiculous. Not everyone is there to work in chemistry. Avoid if you can.

Dr. Fox is truly amazing. She cares about the students success and understands that the transition from high school to uni is tough. She is passionate about chemistry which makes lectures more interesting and is always ready to help. Loved the class!

Amazing prof! Loved her so much. She gives great examples, and lots of them. Her DGD's were very useful, especially around midterm time. And her weekly Sapling Assignments really helped throughout the whole semester. Strongly recommend for 1st year gen chem!!

Harder exams than other profs but they are very fair. Everything on the exam are things that were seen in class, dgds, and assignments. In comparison with gr 12 chemistry, gr 12 chemistry was harder than this course and gr 12 chemistry had way more material then this course.

Do sapling assignments, take good notes and do her old test questions. 90% of her midterms and exam are questions you've done in class, in assignments are she assigned you in the textbook. So if you do your work this course will be an easy A+! Also she is a very fair marker, and will regrade your midterms (she gave me back many marks). Enjoy CHM!
Very clear in her teaching! She gave a lot of her in in DGD's and answered any and all questions asked!
Awesome teacher even if I hated chem!

Everything explained very clearly in class. Lots of opportunities to practise with the online assignments and in-class quizzes, and optional (tricky) practise problems. I enjoyed the lectures. Dr. Fox is also great to talk to in office hours about research and chemistry in general.

Past midterms and exams are a complete blessing as a good portion of her exams are composed of past problems or similar to those. She is clear with expectations posed in class. Although, she can go too fast with difficult concepts and can spend too much time clarifying simple concepts. Sapling assignments are an absolute must as they are a booster.

She is clearly enthusiastic about what she teaches and if you're really interested in chem then you'll like her class but she is very quick and doesn't go over things very clearly.  I found this class very challenging. About 40% of the class failed the first mid term and about 30% failed the second. A LOT of work is needed to do well.

Really nice and helpful prof, just wasn't a fan of her teaching methods. One of the big downsides of being in her class is having class in the UCU. Best prof for CHM 1311, but harder midterms and finals. Do everything she says and you should get a good mark.

Great prof! Explains new concepts very clearly and very slowly (a little too slowly, sometimes which is fine). Course content is relatively hard but she posts a lot of past midterms and exams and most of the exam questions are questions she has already done in dgds or previous evaluations.
Great prof. If you struggle with the content there are a million opportunities for help.

A great lecturer, teaches everything very clearly but sometimes can be a little slow in simple concepts. She posts a bunch of past midterms and finals, all with full solutions, making it very easy to study the material. Overall she is very nice and very helpful!

Honestly one of my favourite profs of my first year. She is very sweet, rewards the students who actually put in the effort , and is a fair marker. There really shouldn't be a reason not to do well in her class if you actually do the work, the resources are all there for you to do well.

Although I really dislike general chemistry, she made the semester tolerable. Her classes are really interesting, she's clear, very friendly, the weight of her midterms and finals aren't too heavy and she gives you a lot of other ways to raise your grade. She always answered my questions clearly. Definitely THE best chem prof.

Dr. Fox is probably the best chm1311 prof there is in the University of Ottawa. However, I don't like how she LOVES to include a lot of ' conversion factors ' in almost 80% of her questions. She DOES NOT use ANY chemistry formulas in class, which is hard if your usually used to using all those equations back in highschool. But overall, easy course.
She made me fall in LOVE with chemistry... I owe her one! YOUR AWESOME DR. FOX!!!!!!
Absolutely love Dr. Fox. Amazing at explaining, extremely helpful in office hours, and very fair exams. I hope to have her in future years :)
Best teacher ever. Best course ever. most interesting chemsitry course I ever had.
The prof is very clear and the course is not very difficult.
She's one of the best chemistry profs i've had. She genuinely cares about her students and her lectures are really organized and engaging. I definately would take it with her again!

Best Prof. She is helpful and if you do EXACTLY what she says you are guaranteed. Lots of the questions from previous exams and midterms are recycled as well as questions from HER dgd section. She is super nice, just don't go ask her a question about something clerical that she said like 20 times in class, if you do you're to blame not her.

Awesome lecturer, so passionate! Definitely get LectureTools, Sapling, and Learnsmart. Every little bit counts. Study using past tests. She gives you a LOT of resources. Midterms/final were challenging but fair. The questions are mostly from past tests, Petrucci, or Silberberg. Labs were pretty easy, but come prepared! Never procrastinate.

Dr. Fox is by far the best professor I've had in my first semester at uOttawa. Her passion for chemistry really extends to her students' success in the class. Her use of lecture tools and in class problems prepare you. Exam was a little more difficult than midterms but she's really fair. Hard work pays off! Thanks for an awesome semester Dr. Fox!
Amazing prof! Very engaging and passionate. Practice and understand her old midterms and exams and you will be fine. She reuses old exam and homework questions for exams.
I love her, I hate chem but i still love her.

Best prof this semester. Don't listen to anyone else saying she is hard. JUST MAKE SURE YOU DO OLD MIDTERMS AND FINALS AND YOU WILL ACE THIS COURSE. She is very clear at what she teaches and makes the class interesting. Also gives out easy marks such as just showing up to class. I would take the course again just for the prof.

The exams are super-hard, compared to homework. But, the secret of getting A is doing the last year exams. She reused the questions of those. Super make sure that you do the last year exams at least twice. Then, you will get over 90%.

Amazing!!! She is the EASIEST prof out of all the CHM1311 profs; (midterms 1&2 avg were 77 and 68, compared to other profs who had 49% class avg). The first half of the course pretty well until she showed up, her final exam DOES NOT reflect material she teaches!! SHE has Crazy application questions she gets out of no where and ur expected to connect/apply ur memory to her applications in exam; shes nice and good lecturer bad very unfair...

Worst prof I had first semester. Her exams are very tricky. Read the questions over and over again. Her final was brutal. Take advantage of the clickers an the MasteringChemistry assignments. Labs for this course were fair but it depends on your TA.

Amazing person and extremely clear presenter. Passionate. Super smart. However, the examination guidelines would like to be improved. The examination did not reflect information covered in class, nor the textbook per se, and it was extremely difficult. Lack of assignments did improve further misunderstanding.

She is an engaging professor in the sense that she is very excited about what she teaches. However, she emphasizes on concepts that don't even show up on the final. Her final consisted of questions that were barely relevant. As a professor who prides herself in the importance of ameliorating the way students learn, she fell very short.

Very passionate and loves teaching the course, but this doesn't make her a good teacher, less than half the material she taught was in the textbook- she rushes through all the other material for which we have no extra resources to study from. Lastly, her exams are written to drop the class avg and do not accurately reflect what we learned in class.

She is a very nice prof, but her midterms are brutal. Class averages were in the mid-to-low 50s. CHM1311 was class that everyone in 1st year science feared. The exam was much easier, however. My best advice is to go to the DGDs that she runs and pay attention - she reuses these questions for the final!
She is a good teacher, with brutal exams. Good classes bad midterms.

She's an amazing prof- great lecturer. She is very enthusiastic and truly cares about her students. She answers questions very clearly and takes all the time in the world to help you understand the concepts. Highly recommend her to anyone! However, her midterms are brutal...
brutal midterm

Dr. Fox is great! She was such an encouraging and enthusiastic professor (she kept me awake and interested during the 8:30 lectures). However, I found her exam to be VERY difficult, especially in comparison to her practice exam! That being said, she's amazing otherwise.
She was a great prof!! Anyone to have her is really lucky :)
Helpful, however the exam was brutally difficult.
Very helpful and passionate about chemistry! A pleasure to listen to :)

AMAZING FIRST YEAR PROF!!I love  how enthusiastic she gets in class. She loves to help anyone, all you have to do is just ask. Extremly friendly and understanding. She<s a nice prof, but you are required either to buy the book, or at least pay for a subscription at Pearson's MasteringChemistry to do your assignments, which is quite annoying since it's 50$ and otherwise useless. Super enthusiastic prof! Always willing to help any student. Midterms and exams are tricky but fair, so be sure to LOOK AT PREVIOUS TESTS! She was the best professor I had during the fall semester. She is very enthusiastic about the course material, and she teaches it in a fun way. Her exams are very simple, and there are no surprises. Her exams were very similar to the practise exams, so it would be smart to take a look at those.
Dr. Fox Rox! Clearly loves teaching and chemistry...which combine to make the ultimate professor! I also like the way she says Kw! Hah!
enthusiastic, very good class notes and seems passionate bout what she is teaching. tricky midterms!!

BEST PROF EVER! I hated chemistry prior to the begining of classes. Now it's the only class that I actually look forward to. Smart, cares about students and teaches with absolute clarity. She's the best!
her exams are a joke, you must be terrible at chem to not do well in her classes. If you want easy marks go with her, but if you want to learn real chemistry, pick ogilvie

Bon professeur qui se soucie de ses lves...si les devoirs assign sont bien faite alors les examens sont plutot facile...la composante laboratoire du cours est cool....compar au autres lab de chimie de d'autre cour...overall, une bonne classe
REALLY GOOD , SHE EXPLAINS VERY WELL AND HER FINAL WAS EASY

GREAT!
